🧩 1. Cascading (JPA/Hibernate)
📌 Concept
Cascading means operations on a parent entity automatically apply to its child entities.
👉 Example:
If you save a User, its Orders should also get saved automatically.

⚙️ Approach
Use cascade attribute in relationships:
@OneToOne
@OneToMany
@ManyToOne
@ManyToMany
Types of Cascade:
Type
Meaning
PERSIST
Save child when parent is saved
MERGE
Update child when parent is updated
REMOVE
Delete child when parent is deleted
REFRESH
Refresh child from DB
DETACH
Detach child from session
ALL
Apply all operations


💻 Code
@Entity
class User {
    @Id
    private Long id;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "user", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<Order> orders;
}

@Entity
class Order {
    @Id
    private Long id;

    @ManyToOne
    private User user;
}


🔑 Key Points
Without cascade → you must manually save child entities
CascadeType.ALL is common but can be risky (especially DELETE)
Use carefully in bi-directional relationships

📘 Learnings
Cascading reduces boilerplate code
Think: “Parent controls lifecycle of child”

🔄 2. Transactional (@Transactional)
📌 Concept
A transaction ensures all DB operations succeed or fail together (ACID).
👉 If one operation fails → everything rolls back.

⚙️ Approach
Use @Transactional on:
Service class (preferred)
Or method level

💻 Code
@Service
class PaymentService {

    @Transactional
    public void transferMoney() {
        debitAccount();
        creditAccount();
    }
}


🔑 Key Points
If exception occurs → rollback
Default: rollback on RuntimeException only
Can customize:
@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)

Avoid using in Controller layer ❌
Best practice: Service layer ✅

📘 Learnings
Ensures data consistency
Critical for banking, payments, bookings

🧠 3. Dirty Checking (Hibernate)
📌 Concept
Hibernate automatically detects changes in entity objects and updates DB without explicit save().
👉 You just modify object → Hibernate tracks → DB updated at transaction end.

⚙️ Approach
Happens inside Persistence Context (Session)
Works only when:
Entity is managed
Inside a transaction

💻 Code
@Transactional
public void updateUser(Long id) {
    User user = entityManager.find(User.class, id);
    user.setName("Vipul");  // No save() call
}

👉 Hibernate automatically runs:
UPDATE user SET name = 'Vipul' WHERE id = ?


🔑 Key Points
No explicit save() needed
Works only inside transaction
Hibernate compares old vs new state

📘 Learnings
Reduces boilerplate updates
Important for performance and clean code

🔥 Final Connection (Very Important)
Concept
Role
Cascading
Controls related entity operations
Transactional
Ensures atomicity
Dirty Checking
Auto updates changed entities

👉 Real-world flow:
@Transactional starts
You modify entity → Dirty Checking tracks
Cascade handles related entities
Transaction commits → all changes saved


